nd Growth: A Formal Analysis of the “Development Channel” -- t12. The Real Exchange Rate and Economic Growth: Some Observations on the Possible Channels -- tPart 4. Finance and Crises -- t13. Capitalism and Financial Crises: A Long-Term Perspective -- t14. Financial Crises, Institutions, and the Macroeconomy -- t15. United States Size Distribution and the Macroeconomy 1986–2009 -- t16. Sovereign Credit Risk in Latin America and Global Common Factors -- tPart 5. Approaches to Development -- t17. Cognitive Dissonance: Postwar Economic Development Strategies and Bretton Woods International Financial Stability -- t18. New Developmentalism as a Weberian Ideal Type -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLatin American neo-structuralism is a cutting-edge, regionally focused economic theory with broad implications for macroeconomics and development economics. Roberto Frenkel has spent five decades developing the theory's core arguments and expanding their application throughout the discipline, revolutionizing our understanding of high inflation and hyperinflation, disinflation programs, and the behavior of foreign exchange markets as well as financial and currency crises in emerging economies.The essays in this collection assess Latin American neo-structuralism's theoretical contributions and viability as the world's economies evolve. The authors discuss Frenkel's work in relation to pricing decisions, inflation and stabilization policy, development and income distribution in Latin America, and macroeconomic policy for economic growth. An entire section focuses on finance and crisis, and the volume concludes with a neo-structuralist analysis of general aspects of economic development. For those seeking a comprehensive introduction to contemporary Latin American economic thought, this collection not only explicates the intricate work of one of its greatest practitioners but also demonstrates its impact on the growth of economics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aEconomic developmentzLatin America. 0aFiscal policyzLatin America. 0aMacroeconomics. 0aMonetary policyzLatin America. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / International / General.2bisacsh1 aBacha, Edmar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarbosa, Nelson, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBonelli, Regis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBresser-Pereira, Luiz Carlos, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarvalho, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCañonero, Gustavo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChisari, Omar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDamill, Mario, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDamill, Mario, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDancourt, Oscar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDreizzen, Julio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFanelli, José María, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerro, Gustavo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFfrench-Davis, Ricardo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeresi, Rodrigo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeymann, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKampel, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKregel, Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKumar, Rishabh, econtr